Yes, the `ESP.getFreeStack()` and `ESP.getStackMax()` functions in the Espressif ESP8266 provide similar functionality to retrieve the free and maximum stack size. The code snippet you provided is correct and will display the free stack size and maximum stack size in the Serial Monitor.

Here's a breakdown of the code:
```c++
void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  delay(100);

  // Check stack size
  uint32_t freeStack = ESP.getFreeStack();
  uint32_t maxStack = ESP.getStackMax();

  Serial.print("Free stack size: ");
  Serial.println(freeStack);

  Serial.print("Maximum stack size: ");
  Serial.println(maxStack);
}
```
By including this code in the `setup()` function and opening the Serial Monitor at a baud rate of 115200, you will see the free stack size and maximum stack size printed in the Serial Monitor.

Certainly! Here's an example code that demonstrates how to display the free and maximum stack size using the ESP8266 core by the ESP8266 Community:

```c++
#include <ESP8266WiFi.h>

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  delay(100);

  // Check stack size
  uint32_t freeStack = ESP.getFreeContStack();
  uint32_t maxStack = ESP.getMaxContStack();

  Serial.print("Free stack size: ");
  Serial.println(freeStack);

  Serial.print("Maximum stack size: ");
  Serial.println(maxStack);
}

void loop() {
  // Do nothing
}
```

In this code, the `ESP.getFreeContStack()` function is used to retrieve the free stack size, and the `ESP.getMaxContStack()` function is used to retrieve the maximum stack size. The values are then printed in the Serial Monitor.

Once you upload and run this code on your ESP8266 board, open the Serial Monitor in the Arduino IDE at a baud rate of 115200. You should see the free stack size and maximum stack size printed in the Serial Monitor.

Please note that the stack sizes reported by these functions refer to the continuous stack memory available to the program, not the overall heap memory. Additionally, remember to include the necessary `#include <ESP8266WiFi.h>` for accessing these stack-related functions.

